IbarakiKasen:
Personally I suggest using firewall for security purpose. You can run the server in a dedicated user and use iptables -m owner to drop the outgoing connections.. @kaoet I think using original domain in forwarding is a documented feature instead of a bug.
Passing the domain to outbound relay will allow the relay server do the DNS resolve on its own, to obtain a answer based on the server location (GeoDNS) and the network stack it supports (some of my relay server support IPv6 while others don't). Together with the inbound option domainOverride, I can do this more aggressively in transparent proxy.
In your case maybe you want to reuse the resolved IP for freedom outbound, which is different from my use case. But it seems that there is also some load balancing mechanism in freedom for better handling domains that resolves to multiple IPs, which makes adding the feature more complex.
Implementing this for a specific outbound type will increase the complexity of this project. Instead I always recommend using solid security tools on security needs (iptables/apparmor/selinux for limiting outbound connections, and fail2ban for banning malicious user).. Use the following configure as your "inbound" or put it in the "inboundDetour" list:
json
{
  "port": 3128,
  "listen": "127.0.0.1",
  "protocol": "http",
  "settings": {
    "timeout": 0
  }
}
